{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8a9f4a27d0dba7f6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tTechnical Report for MERL’s Real-TSE\n2\tChallenge Submission\n3\tDominik Klement∗1,2 , Yoshiki Masuyama1 , Christoph Boeddeker1 ,\n4\tKohei Saijo3 , Julius Richter1 , Gordon Wichern1 , Jonathan Le Roux1\n5\t1\n6\t\n7\tarXiv:2607.09043v1 [eess.AS] 10 Jul 2026\n8\t\n9\t2\n10\t\n11\tMitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories, Cambridge, USA,\n12\tSpeech@FIT, Brno University of Technology, Czechia, 3 Mitsubishi Electric Corporation, Kanagawa, Japan\n13\t\n14\tAbstract—Target speech extraction (TSE) has largely been\n15\tdominated by neural network-based approaches trained and\n16\tevaluated on synthetic fully overlapped data. The Real-TSE\n17\tChallenge aims to advance performance on real-world farfield noisy and reverberant recordings. This technical report\n18\tdescribes MERL’s submission to the Real-TSE Challenge. Rather\n19\tthan proposing a novel model architecture, we built upon the\n20\tbaseline model and focused primarily on data preparation and\n21\tcleaning. Our system was trained in four stages, beginning\n22\twith pre-training on fully overlapped mixtures and simulated\n23\tmulti-talker conversations with noise and reverberation applied\n24\tto both the mixture and the enrollment utterances. We then\n25\tadapted the model to real-world conditions using noisy farfield recordings with pseudo-targets derived from processed\n26\tclose-talk microphone signals. Our submission achieved first\n27\tplace in the second track, demonstrating the critical importance\n28\tof high-quality data preparation. Furthermore, we observed\n29\tthat DNSMOS and speaker similarity are susceptible to overoptimization, motivating an investigation of their robustness using\n30\tadversarial attacks. The results show that both metrics can be\n31\tdriven to extreme values without degrading the token error rate\n32\tor the VAD-based F1 score.\n33\tIndex Terms—Target speaker extraction, Speech Separation\n34\t\n35\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n36\tTarget speaker extraction (TSE) aims to extract a speaker\n37\tof interest from a speech mixture, potentially corrupted by\n38\tnoise or reverberation. Many existing approaches are trained\n39\tand evaluated on simulated datasets, such as Libri2Mix [1],\n40\twhere they achieve improvements exceeding 20 dB SI-SDRi.\n41\tHowever, these models often fail to generalize to real-world\n42\trecordings, such as CHiME-6 [2] and DipCo [3], which exhibit substantially more challenging acoustic conditions. This\n43\tperformance degradation is primarily caused by the domain\n44\tgap between simulated training data and real-world evaluation\n45\tdata.\n46\tTo address this challenge, the authors of the Real-T\n47\tdataset [4] introduced a challenging development and evaluation benchmark comprising both English and Chinese recordings. The long recordings are post-processed into conversational speech mixtures of up to one minute in duration with\n48\tmultiple speakers.\n49\tIn this report, we present our submission to the RealTSE\n50\tChallenge, which builds on the baseline model architecture.\n51\tRather than developing a more powerful model, we focus on\n52\t∗ Work done while Dominik Klement was an intern at MERL.\n53\t\n54\tdata preprocessing and training with real far-field conversational mixtures. Our results demonstrate that strong performance can be achieved with a relatively simple model when\n55\tpaired with an effective data processing and training pipeline.\n56\tII. M ODEL\n57\tWe decided to use one of the provided baseline models\n58\tBand-split RNN (BSRNN) with multi-level speaker conditioning [5] that utilizes per-frame and pooled speaker embeddings\n59\tfor speaker conditioning.\n60\tCompared to the baseline configuration, we replaced\n61\tEcapaTDNN-512 with EcapaTDNN-1024 [6], which is a\n62\tlarger and more powerful speaker embedding model. We also\n63\tincreased the depth of the BSRNN model from 6 to 10\n64\tblocks. This modification significantly improved the extraction\n65\tperformance.\n66\tIII. DATA P ROCESSING\n67\tIn this section, we describe our multi-stage data processing pipeline, consisting of cleaning single-speaker data for\n68\tsimulated pre-training and processing far-field and close-talk\n69\tmixture pairs for real noisy data training.\n70\tA. Pre-training Speech Data Processing\n71\tWe combine data from multiple open datasets containing vast amounts of speakers and speaking style variability:\n72\tLibriSpeech [7], VoxCeleb2 [8], Emilia-YODAS English and\n73\tChinese [9], VCTK [10], and EARS [11].\n74\tFirst, we applied ClearerVoice [12] speech enhancement\n75\tmodels based on masking MOSSFormer [13] to preprocess\n76\tthe noisy corpora such as VoxCeleb2 and Emilia-YODAS.\n77\tThen, we computed speaker cosine similarity between the\n78\toriginal and the enhanced recordings using a pre-trained\n79\tResNet34 model from WeSpeaker [14] to further filter out\n80\tdata with speaker similarity lower than 0.85. We observed that\n81\tthe outliers with speaker similarity lower than 0.5 contained\n82\tmultiple speakers or severe degradation that the enhancement\n83\tcould not clean up. Furthermore, we applied another filtering\n84\tto only consider audio with DNSMOS above 3.0. Even though\n85\ta high DNSMOS score does not guarantee clean speech, this\n86\tfiltering step ensured that the enhancement likely produced\n87\testimates accurate enough for training.\n88\tAfterwards, we computed word-level alignments using\n89\tMontreal Forced Aligner (MFA) [15] to avoid sampling nonspeech segments as target speaker enrollments. Although such\n90\t\n91\t\fsegments could help train the model not to always expect the\n92\ttarget speaker to be present in the mixture, they would make\n93\tit difficult to precisely control their proportion during training.\n94\tInstead, with a probability of 5%, we explicitly generated nontarget samples by pairing the enrollment with a speaker absent\n95\tfrom the input mixture and trained the model to produce a zero\n96\toutput.\n97\tB. Noises and Room Impulse Responses\n98\tWe applied room impulse responses (RIRs) on a clean\n99\tinput mixture and enrollment independently with a probability\n100\tof 0.8. The RIRs were randomly sampled from DNS4 [16]\n101\tand from synthetic impulse responses simulated using Pyroomacoustics [17] with weights 0.8 and 0.2, respectively. We\n102\tpurposely simulated larger rooms to cover the scenarios of\n103\textreme echoes.\n104\tFurthermore, to increase the robustness against multiple\n105\tnoises, we used the following noise databases containing\n106\tmore stationary and also impulsive noises: CHiME-3 [18],\n107\tDEMAND [19], DNS4 [16], FMA [20], FSD50K [21], MUSAN [22], WHAM! [23], and simulated Wind noises from the\n108\tURGENT challenge [24].\n109\tWe used weighted sampling to increase the weight towards\n110\tthe stationary-like noises, where we set the probability of\n111\tsampling CHiME3, WHAM!, and Wind noises to 0.15, and\n112\tthe probability of all the other noises to 0.11. We randomly\n113\tsampled SNR from a [−5, 15] dB range and added the noise to\n114\tthe input mixture and enrollment with probability 0.8. Mixture\n115\tand enrollment noises were selected independently, covering\n116\tall combinations of clean and noisy mixture and enrollment\n117\tpairs during training.\n118\tC. Real Data Processing\n119\tTo include real-world data for training, we utilized CHiME6 [2], AMI [25], AISHELL-4 [26], and AISHELL-5 [27]. As\n120\tAISHELL-5 provides close-talk recordings that are already\n121\tsynchronized with far-field microphones and do not contain\n122\tsignificant cross-talk, we only perform speech enhancement\n123\tusing ClearerVoice. For AISHELL-4, we perform GSS [28]\n124\ton multi-channel audio using ground-truth speaker diarization\n125\tand apply speech enhancement afterwards. During training, we\n126\tuse both AISHELL datasets for simulated far-field mixtures\n127\tonly, as both contain a low amount of overlapped speech.\n128\tSingle-talker Far-field Mixtures: To further adapt the model\n129\tto real noisy data, we select single-talker segments of speech\n130\tbased on the provided dataset annotations. Then, we cut out the\n131\tsame segment from the speaker’s close-talk microphone and\n132\taverage all the close-talk channels if multiple are available,\n133\tand proceed with applying ClearerVoice speech enhancement\n134\tto denoise and dereverberate the close talk.\n135\tTo enable training on such mixtures, we perform max-peak\n136\tcross-correlation synchronization with maximum lag set to\n137\tone second. Afterwards, inspired by [29], we apply a causal\n138\tWiener filter with 10 ms window (160 taps) to project the\n139\tclose-talk signal to the corresponding far-field. To ensure that\n140\tsuch filter can be estimated, we shift the close-talk microphone\n141\t\n142\tby a quarter of the width of the Wiener filter such that the farfield recording is ahead of the corresponding close-talk.\n143\tAfter projecting the close-talk to the corresponding far-field,\n144\twe observed that the projected signal contains noises, caused\n145\tby the fact that the far-field recording contains noise. Hence,\n146\twe apply speech enhancement once more at the very end to\n147\tclean up the projected close-talk.\n148\tBefore training, we use Nvidia Parakeet-V2 [30] to filter\n149\tout all the utterances with WER higher than 30%. We do not\n150\tperform WER-based filtering on AISHELL datasets, as these\n151\tare relatively simple and clean data compared to CHiME-6 or\n152\tAMI.\n153\tDuring mixing, to prevent potential device or channel classification, we simulate far-field mixtures on-the-fly using the\n154\tspeakers from the same session, device, and the same channel.\n155\tReal Far-field Mixture Training: First, we find multi-talker\n156\tconversational segments with max duration 30 s with at least 2\n157\tactive speakers. Then, we find an enrollment for each speaker\n158\tthat is at least 10 seconds long, the majority of which is\n159\tspeech. Afterwards, we use the best-performing TSE model\n160\ttrained on far-field mixtures to reduce cross-talk on CHiME6 and AMI close-talk microphones. The Parakeet-V2 ASR is\n161\tthen used to filter out segments with WER above 50% on\n162\tCHiME-6 and 30% on AMI, keeping the rest of the close-talk\n163\tfar-field pairs for training. At the end, we perform synchronization and close-to-distant projection as described above, and\n164\tapply speech enhancement to get rid of the projection noise.\n165\tIV. T RAINING C URRICULUM\n166\tIt has been shown in [31] that multi-stage curriculum pretraining starting from easier data and gradually progressing\n167\ttowards more challenging data increases model performance,\n168\tgeneralization, and convergence. Therefore, we performed\n169\ttraining in 4-stages.\n170\tA. Fully-overlapped Pre-training\n171\tWe start with pre-training the TSE model from scratch\n172\tusing fully-overlapped Libri2Mix-style data simulated on-thefly with randomly sampled enrollments.\n173\tDuring this stage, the model should learn the mapping\n174\tbetween the enrollment and the mixture, and extract the target\n175\tspeaker. This training phase is performed for 200k training\n176\tsteps.\n177\tB. Noisy Simulated Conversations\n178\tNext, we initialize the model from the previous stage\n179\tand train the model using on-the-fly generated conversational\n180\tmixtures simulated by a modified FastMSS [32] simulator.\n181\tDuring this stage, we also introduce reverberation and noise\n182\tto increase the model’s robustness.\n183\tC. Far-field Mixtures\n184\tAfter the second pre-training stage, we continue training\n185\ton on-the-fly simulated far-field mixtures generated from\n186\tsingle-talker segments of CHiME-6, AMI, AISHELL-4, and\n187\tAISHELL-5. Enrollment utterances are randomly sampled\n188\t\n189\t\ffrom the same segments. Since AMI does not contain background noise, we augment both the mixtures and the enrollment utterances with artificial noise with a probability of 0.2.\n190\t\n191\tTABLE I\n192\tC OMPARISON BETWEEN THE CHALLENGE BASELINE , DIFFERENT\n193\tTRAINING STAGES AND THE ADVERSARIAL ATTACK ON THE DEV S ET.. P\n194\tSTANDS FOR PRECISION , R FOR RECALL , AND SPK FOR SPEAKER TO\n195\tENROLLMENT COSINE SIMILARITY. T HE MODEL IN THE LAST ROW\n196\t\n197\tD. Real Far-field Mixtures\n198\t\n199\tMARKED WITH ⋆ WAS TRAINED ONLY USING RECONSTRUCTION LOSSES\n200\tDURING ALL STAGES .\n201\t\n202\tLastly, the fourth stage contains real noisy mixture training\n203\tagainst targets that were extracted by our previous TSE model.\n204\tTo increase the variability during this training stage, we mix\n205\tin 20% of synthetic data, and around 30% of far-field mixtures\n206\tfrom the third stage of training.\n207\t\n208\tModel\n209\t\n210\tTER\n211\t\n212\tP\n213\t\n214\tR\n215\t\n216\tF1\n217\t\n218\tSPK\n219\t\n220\tOVRL\n221\t\n222\tP.808\n223\t\n224\t1st stage\n225\t+ 2nd stage\n226\t+ 3rd stage\n227\t+ 4th stage\n228\t\n229\t0.53\n230\t0.44\n231\t0.39\n232\t0.37\n233\t\n234\t0.82\n235\t0.88\n236\t0.91\n237\t0.93\n238\t\n239\t0.93\n240\t0.88\n241\t0.86\n242\t0.85\n243\t\n244\t0.86\n245\t0.86\n246\t0.88\n247\t0.88\n248\t\n249\t0.48\n250\t0.47\n251\t0.54\n252\t0.55\n253\t\n254\t2.42\n255\t2.37\n256\t2.81\n257\t2.84\n258\t\n259\t3.21\n260\t3.15\n261\t3.15\n262\t3.33\n263\t\n264\t4 stages, Pure\n265\t\n266\t0.37\n267\t\n268\t0.93\n269\t\n270\t0.84\n271\t\n272\t0.87\n273\t\n274\t0.47\n275\t\n276\t2.89\n277\t\n278\t3.32\n279\t\n280\tV. T RAINING S ETUP\n281\tDuring the first two stages, we optimized the following\n282\ttime-domain loss function:\n283\t!\n284\tB\n285\t1 X\n286\ttime\n287\t|yi − x̂i | ,\n288\t(1)\n289\tL\n290\t= log\n291\tB i=1\n292\twhere x̂i is the prediction and yi is the corresponding target,\n293\tand B is the mini-batch size. Optimizing this loss instead\n294\tof SI-SNR or SNR prevents numerical errors for zero targets (i.e., total silence). The loss function was optimized\n295\tusing AdamW [33] optimizer with learning rate (LR) 0.0005\n296\tand weight decay 0.001. We used the ReduceLROnPlateau1\n297\tlearning rate scheduler according to the validation SNR. The\n298\ttraining recordings were randomly cropped to eight seconds\n299\twhile target speaker speech presence was ensured according\n300\tto the aligned word-level timestamps.\n301\tDuring the last two stages, we used linear LR warmup for\n302\t2k steps with peak LR set to 1e − 4 and then applied cosine\n303\tlearning rate scheduler [34]. Because the targets are enhanced\n304\tprojections and not the true clean signals, the phase between\n305\tthe far-field mixture and the projected close-talk might not be\n306\twell aligned. Hence, we utilize magnitude-based multi-scale\n307\tSTFT (MS-STFT) loss during the last two training stages,\n308\tdefined as:\n309\tLstft =\n310\t\n311\tK\n312\tB X\n313\tX\n314\t\n315\t∥|S(yi , wk , hk )| − |S(x̂i , wk , hk )|∥1 ,\n316\t\n317\t(2)\n318\t\n319\ti=1 k=1\n320\t\n321\twhere S(yi , wk , hk ) represents STFT computed with the window length wk and hop length hk . We selected hk = 41 wk\n322\tsamples. We used 5 window lengths: 100, 200, 400, 800, 1600,\n323\twhich corresponds to 6.25 ms, 12.5 ms, 25 ms, 50 ms, 100 ms.\n324\tAs described before, during the fourth stage, we mixed in a\n325\tsmall portion of simulated data, so that we could utilize the\n326\ttime-domain loss Ltime on that data.\n327\tBesides the reconstruction losses, we also utilized metricaware losses. First, we used a torch-based implementation of\n328\tDNSMOS that allowed us to backpropagate through it and\n329\toptimize the following loss function:\n330\tB\n331\t\n332\tLMOS =\n333\t\n334\t1 X\n335\t2\n336\t(5.0 − DNSMOSovrl (x̂i )) .\n337\tB i=1\n338\t\n339\t1 PyTorch - ReduceLROnPlateau\n340\t\n341\t(3)\n342\t\n343\tDNSMOS\n344\t\n345\tSimilarly, to slightly push the model to better preserve the\n346\tenrollment speaker identity, we optimized a cosine similarity\n347\tbetween the enrollment and the output:\n348\tB\n349\t\n350\tLspk =\n351\t\n352\t1 X\n353\tpred\n354\t1.0 − cos(eenrl\n355\ti , ei ) ,\n356\tB i=1\n357\t\n358\t(4)\n359\t\n360\tpred\n361\twhere eenrl\n362\trepresent the corresponding speaker embedi , ei\n363\tdings extracted using ResNet34 from the enrollment and the\n364\tprediction, respectively.\n365\tThe final loss for the third and fourth stage training is a\n366\tweighted combination of all the preceeding losses:\n367\t\n368\tL = 10Lstft + Ltime + 0.01LMOS + Lspk ,\n369\t\n370\t(5)\n371\t\n372\twhere Ltime is only computed on the simulated part of the\n373\ttraining batch.\n374\tVI. R ESULTS\n375\tTable I shows the progressive improvements in all of the\n376\tmetrics. First, TER significantly improves between the first\n377\tand the second stage, proving that conversational simulated\n378\tdata with heavy augmentations improve the TSE performance\n379\ton challenging far-field data. Furthermore, training with 3rd\n380\tand 4th stage shows that using real noisy and reverberated\n381\tdata for training improves the performance even further.\n382\tIn terms of spk-sim and DNSMOS, the main improvement\n383\tcomes from slight metric tuning, which we used to balance out\n384\tthese metrics with TER and F1. However, we observed that\n385\ttraining using these metrics did not improve the perceptual\n386\tquality when listening to the extracted audio. We even observed that over-tuning to speaker similarity causes the TSE\n387\tmodel to output target-speaker-like artifacts in the presence of\n388\tnoise even if no one speaks. This further proves how brittle\n389\tthe speaker similarity models are.\n390\tTo show the effects metric optimization had on our submission, we performed a four-stage training again without\n391\tusing the metric-aware losses during the last two stages. In\n392\tthis case, the model was trained using Lstft on all data and\n393\tLtime on simulated-only data. The last row (“Pure”) in Table I\n394\tshows that we could achieve the same TER and DNSMOS\n395\tas with metric-aware fine-tuning. Also, F 1 score only slightly\n396\t\n397\t\fdecreased compared to the metric-aware training model due\n398\tto the lower recall. This was likely caused by not optimizing\n399\tfor spk-sim, which usually forced the model to leak more\n400\tnoise that could potentially trigger the VAD system. The only\n401\tmetric that got significantly decreased is speaker similarity,\n402\twhose value remains equal to that at the end of the second\n403\ttraining stage. After listening to a few examples between the\n404\tmetric-optimized and the pure model, we could not hear any\n405\tsignificant difference in terms of extracted speaker identity,\n406\tproving how overoptimistic the metric value can get once we\n407\tstart optimizing it.\n408\t\n409\tAlgorithm 1: Metric Attack.\n410\tdef attack(inp, enrl):\n411\tdelta = nn.Parameter(torch.zeros_like(inp))\n412\toptim = Adam([delta], lr=1e-3)\n413\tfor i in range(200):\n414\tdelta_t = tanh(delta) * 0.01\n415\taudio_t = (inp + delta_t).clamp(-1, 1)\n416\tloss = (stft(audio_t).abs() - stft(inp).abs())\n417\tloss = loss.pow().mean()\n418\tloss = loss + (5.0 - dnsmos(inp))ˆ2\n419\tloss = loss + (1.0 - spksim(inp, enrl))\n420\toptim.zero_grads()\n421\tloss.backward()\n422\toptim.step()\n423\t\n424\tVII. M ETRIC ATTACK\n425\t“When a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be\n426\ta good measure.”\n427\t— Goodhart’s law\n428\tMany speech separation and target speech extraction systems optimize evaluation metrics either explicitly or implicitly during training, including metrics such as SI-SDR and\n429\tPESQ. From the perspective of Goodhart’s Law, this practice\n430\tfundamentally compromises the validity of such metrics as\n431\tevaluation tools: once a metric becomes an optimization target,\n432\tit ceases to function as an independent measure of system\n433\tquality.\n434\tThis issue is particularly evident for non-intrusive neuralnetwork-based metrics. For example, clean speech recordings\n435\tfrom datasets such as VCTK achieve DNSMOS scores of only\n436\taround 3.2 [35]. Therefore, observing multiple leaderboard\n437\tsubmissions with DNSMOS scores exceeding 3.5 raised concerns about the susceptibility of model-based metrics to overoptimization.\n438\tNeural networks are universal function approximators that\n439\tcan approximate arbitrary functions given sufficient capacity\n440\tand width [36]. Consequently, when a metric is directly\n441\toptimized during training, a sufficiently expressive model\n442\tcan effectively learn the metric itself and, in the extreme\n443\tcase, internalize at training time an adversarial attack required\n444\tto maximize its score. The main technical challenge to do\n445\tso is carefully balancing the optimization process to avoid\n446\tdegrading performance on other evaluation criteria such as\n447\tTER and F1. Given the better-than-clean-speech DNSMOS\n448\tscores we observed on the leaderboard, we suspect some teams\n449\tmay have unintentionally performed such an adversarial attack.\n450\tTo demonstrate the upper bound of metric-aware training\n451\tand illustrate how metric optimization during training can\n452\tinvalidate the optimized metrics as evaluation measures, we\n453\tconducted a series of per-utterance adversarial attacks using\n454\tdifferent metric combinations. We were surprised by how\n455\teasily a barely perceptible perturbation could be added to the\n456\ttarget speech extraction output waveform, yielding state-ofthe-art (but perceptually meaningless) DNSMOS and speakersimilarity scores while preserving performance on the remaining metrics, including TER and F1.\n457\tWe based our attack algorithm on [37], which is straightforward and described in Algorithm 1. It performs 200 steps,\n458\tin which we first calculate a small delta and add it to the\n459\t\n460\treturn audio_t\n461\t\n462\twaveform, then compute all the losses and sum them with\n463\tunit weights. It is important to note that we heavily regularize\n464\tthe adversarial noise energy and also minimize the difference\n465\tbetween the original and modified magnitude spectrograms\n466\tto prevent large changes. Finally, we backpropagate the loss\n467\tgradients through the metric models and update the delta using\n468\tthe Adam optimizer. We observed during the experiments that\n469\tno special loss weights, learning rate, or number of steps\n470\ttuning was required for successful convergence, proving the\n471\tsimplicity of the attack.\n472\tTABLE II\n473\tC OMPARISON BETWEEN BEFORE AND AFTER METRIC ATTACK .\n474\tAttack\n475\t\n476\tTER\n477\t\n478\tP\n479\t\n480\tR\n481\t\n482\tF1\n483\t\n484\tSPK\n485\t\n486\tNone\n487\tDNSMOS\n488\tSPK-SIM (EN)\n489\t+ DNSMOS\n490\t+ SPK-SIM (CN)\n491\t\n492\t0.37\n493\t0.37\n494\t0.37\n495\t0.37\n496\t0.37\n497\t\n498\t0.94\n499\t0.94\n500\t0.94\n501\t0.94\n502\t0.94\n503\t\n504\t0.85\n505\t0.85\n506\t0.85\n507\t0.85\n508\t0.85\n509\t\n510\t0.88\n511\t0.88\n512\t0.88\n513\t0.88\n514\t0.88\n515\t\n516\t0.52\n517\t0.52\n518\t0.82\n519\t0.82\n520\t0.99\n521\t\n522\tDNSMOS\n523\tOVRL P808\n524\t2.83\n525\t4.18\n526\t2.80\n527\t4.11\n528\t4.07\n529\t\n530\t3.33\n531\t3.33\n532\t3.33\n533\t3.33\n534\t3.33\n535\t\n536\tTable II shows the model results before the adversarial\n537\tattack in the first row. It can be seen that attacking DNSMOS\n538\tonly (2nd row) does not change the unattacked metrics. Also,\n539\twe can see that attacking only the English spk-sim model does\n540\tnot achieve an overall score close to 1, as the Chinese speaker\n541\tsimilarity stays at around 0.5 even after the attack. The last row\n542\tshows the scenario where DNSMOS and speaker models for\n543\tEnglish and Chinese are attacked. Once again, we can see that\n544\tTER and F1 stayed the same, while spk-sim and DNSMOS\n545\tare achieving their extremes. It is noteworthy to observe that\n546\tattacking only DNSMOS achieves the best DNSMOS score\n547\tout of all the attacks. The score decreases as we increase\n548\tthe number of simultaneously-attacked metrics. However, the\n549\trelative change in DNSMOS between attacking all the metrics\n550\tand only DNSMOS is negligible relative to its value.\n551\tGiven the fragility of non-intrusive metrics as demonstrated\n552\tby our attack and also shown in [37], [38], we suggest that\n553\tthe Challenge Organizers either remove DNSMOS and spksim when calculating the official ranking or replace them\n554\t\n555\t\fwith alternative speech quality and speaker similarity metrics\n556\tthat were not attacked either advertently or inadvertently by\n557\tsubmitted systems.\n558\tVIII. C ONCLUSION\n559\tIn this work, we described our submission to the RealTSE\n560\tchallenge, consisting of the baseline TSE model architecture and multi-stage data processing and training curriculum.\n561\tOur results confirmed that each training stage improved the\n562\tmetrics, proving that thorough data preparation with heavy\n563\tmixture and enrollment augmentations and real noisy data\n564\ttraining can push the performance even further. We also\n565\tshowed that metrics such as speaker similarity or DNSMOS\n566\tare brittle and susceptible to adversarial attacks. To push it\n567\tto the extreme, we applied a per-waveform adversarial attack,\n568\twhich serves as an upperbound of what can be potentially\n569\tachieved with training-time optimization if enough capacity\n570\tand training balance is achieved. This raises challenges for the\n571\torganization of future challenges in an age where generative\n572\tmodels are thriving, and suggests the need for further metric\n573\tdevelopment, which will be focus of our future work.\n574\tR EFERENCES\n575\t[1] J. Cosentino, M. Pariente, S. Cornell, A. Deleforge, and E. Vincent,\n576\t“LibriMix: An open-source dataset for generalizable speech separation,”\n577\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2005.11262, 2020.\n578\t[2] S. Watanabe, M. Mandel, J. Barker, E. Vincent, A. Arora, X. Chang,\n579\tS. Khudanpur, V. Manohar, D. Povey, D. Raj, D. Snyder, A. S. Subramanian, J. Trmal, B. B. Yair, C. Boeddeker, Z. Ni, Y. Fujita, S. Horiguchi,\n580\tN. Kanda, T. Yoshioka, and N. Ryant, “CHiME-6 challenge: Tackling\n581\tmultispeaker speech recognition for unsegmented recordings,” in Proc.\n582\t6th International Workshop on Speech Processing in Everyday Environments (CHiME 2020), 2020, pp. 1–7.\n583\t[3] M. Van Segbroeck, A. Zaid, K. Kutsenko, C. Huerta, T. Nguyen, X. Luo,\n584\tB. Hoffmeister, J. Trmal, M. Omologo, and R. Maas, “DiPCo – dinner\n585\tparty corpus,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2020, pp. 434–436.\n586\t[4] S. Li, S. Wang, J. Han, K. Zhang, W. Wang, and H. Li, “REAL-T:\n587\tReal conversational mixtures for target speaker extraction,” in Proc.\n588\tInterspeech, 2025, pp. 1923–1927.\n589\t[5] K. Zhang, J. Li, S. Wang, Y. Wei, Y. Wang, Y. Wang, and H. Li,\n590\t“Multi-level speaker representation for target speaker extraction,” in\n591\tProc. ICASSP, 2025.\n592\t[6] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck, “ECAPA-TDNN:\n593\tEmphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in TDNN\n594\tbased speaker verification,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2020, pp. 3830–3834.\n595\t[7] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “LibriSpeech: An\n596\tASR corpus based on public domain audio books,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n597\t2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n598\t[8] J. S. Chung, A. Nagrani, and A. Zisserman, “VoxCeleb2: Deep speaker\n599\trecognition,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2018, pp. 1086–1090.\n600\t[9] H. He, Z. Shang, C. Wang, X. Li, Y. Gu, H. Hua, L. Liu, C. Yang,\n601\tJ. Li, P. Shi, Y. Wang, K. Chen, P. Zhang, and Z. Wu, “Emilia: A largescale, extensive, multilingual, and diverse dataset for speech generation,”\n602\tIEEE/ACM Trans. Audio, Speech, Lang. Process., vol. 33, pp. 4044–\n603\t4054, 2025.\n604\t[10] J. Yamagishi, C. Veaux, and K. MacDonald, “CSTR VCTK Corpus:\n605\tEnglish multi-speaker corpus for CSTR voice cloning toolkit (version\n606\t0.92),” 2019.\n607\t[11] J. Richter, Y.-C. Wu, S. Krenn, S. Welker, B. Lay, S. Watanabe,\n608\tA. Richard, and T. Gerkmann, “EARS: An anechoic fullband speech\n609\tdataset benchmarked for speech enhancement and dereverberation,” in\n610\tProc. Interspeech, 2024, pp. 4873–4877.\n611\t[12] S. Zhao, Z. Pan, and B. Ma, “ClearerVoice-Studio: Bridging advanced\n612\tspeech processing research and practical deployment,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2025, pp. 2980–2984.\n613\t\n614\t[13] S. Zhao and B. Ma, “MossFormer: Pushing the performance limit of\n615\tmonaural speech separation using gated single-head transformer with\n616\tconvolution-augmented joint self-attentions,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2023.\n617\t[14] H. Wang, C. Liang, S. Wang, Z. Chen, B. Zhang, X. Xiang, Y. Deng,\n618\tand Y. Qian, “WeSpeaker: A research and production oriented speaker\n619\tembedding learning toolkit,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2023.\n620\t[15] M. McAuliffe, M. Socolof, S. Mihuc, M. Wagner, and M. Sonderegger,\n621\t“Montreal forced aligner: Trainable text-speech alignment using Kaldi,”\n622\tin Proc. Interspeech, 2017, pp. 498–502.\n623\t[16] H. Dubey, V. Gopal, R. Cutler, A. Aazami, S. Matusevych, S. Braun,\n624\tS. E. Eskimez, M. Thakker, T. Yoshioka, H. Gamper, and R. Aichner,\n625\t“ICASSP 2022 deep noise suppression challenge,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n626\t2022, pp. 9271–9275.\n627\t[17] R. Scheibler, E. Bezzam, and I. Dokmanić, “Pyroomacoustics: A python\n628\tpackage for audio room simulation and array processing algorithms,” in\n629\tProc. ICASSP, 2018, pp. 351–355.\n630\t[18] J. Barker, R. Marxer, E. Vincent, and S. Watanabe, “The third CHiME\n631\tspeech separation and recognition challenge: Dataset, task and baselines,” in Proc. ASRU, Dec. 2015, pp. 504–511.\n632\t[19] J. Thiemann, N. Ito, and E. Vincent, “The diverse environments multichannel acoustic noise database (DEMAND): A database of multichannel environmental noise recordings,” in Proceedings of Meetings on\n633\tAcoustics, vol. 19, no. 1. Acoustical Society of America, 2013, p.\n634\t035081.\n635\t[20] M. Defferrard, K. Benzi, P. Vandergheynst, and X. Bresson, “FMA: A\n636\tdataset for music analysis,” in Proc. ISMIR, 2017, pp. 316–323.\n637\t[21] E. Fonseca, X. Favory, J. Pons, F. Font, and X. Serra, “FSD50K: An\n638\topen dataset of human-labeled sound events,” IEEE/ACM Trans. Audio,\n639\tSpeech, Lang. Process., vol. 30, pp. 829–852, 2022.\n640\t[22] D. Snyder, G. Chen, and D. Povey, “MUSAN: A music, speech, and\n641\tnoise corpus,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1510.08484, 2015.\n642\t[23] G. Wichern, J. Antognini, M. Flynn, L. R. Zhu, E. McQuinn, D. Crow,\n643\tE. Manilow, and J. Le Roux, “WHAM!: Extending speech separation to\n644\tnoisy environments,” in Interspeech 2019, 2019.\n645\t[24] W. Zhang, R. Scheibler, K. Saijo, S. Cornell, C. Li, Z. Ni, J. Pirklbauer, M. Sach, S. Watanabe, T. Fingscheidt, and Y. Qian, “URGENT\n646\tchallenge: Universality, robustness, and generalizability for speech enhancement,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2024, pp. 4868–4872.\n647\t[25] J. Carletta, S. Ashby, S. Bourban, M. Flynn, M. Guillemot, T. Hain,\n648\tJ. Kadlec, V. Karaiskos, W. Kraaij, M. Kronenthal et al., “The AMI\n649\tmeeting corpus: A pre-announcement,” in International workshop on\n650\tmachine learning for multimodal interaction. Springer, 2005, pp. 28–\n651\t39.\n652\t[26] Y. Fu, L. Cheng, S. Lv, Y. Jv, Y. Kong, Z. Chen, Y. Hu, L. Xie, J. Wu,\n653\tH. Bu, X. Xu, J. Du, and J. Chen, “AISHELL-4: An open source dataset\n654\tfor speech enhancement, separation, recognition and speaker diarization\n655\tin conference scenario,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2021, pp. 3665–3669.\n656\t[27] Y. Dai, H. Wang, X. Li, Z. Zhang, S. Wang, L. Xie, X. Xu, H. Guo,\n657\tS. Zhang, H. Bu, and W. Chen, “AISHELL-5: The first open-source\n658\tin-car multi-channel multi-speaker speech dataset for automatic speech\n659\tdiarization and recognition,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2025, pp. 5493–5497.\n660\t[28] C. Boeddecker, J. Heitkaemper, J. Schmalenstroeer, L. Drude, J. Heymann, and R. Haeb-Umbach, “Front-end processing for the CHiME-5\n661\tdinner party scenario,” in Proc. 5th International Workshop on Speech\n662\tProcessing in Everyday Environments (CHiME 2018), 2018, pp. 35–40.\n663\t[29] T. Nakatani, R. Ikeshita, N. Kamo, M. Delcroix, and S. Araki, “Generating training targets for real-world speech enhancement via closeto-distant microphone projection,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2026, pp. 18 912–\n664\t18 916.\n665\t[30] M. Sekoyan, N. R. Koluguri, N. Tadevosyan, P. Zelasko, T. Bartley,\n666\tN. Karpov, J. Balam, and B. Ginsburg, “Canary-1B-V2 & ParakeetTDT-0.6B-V3: Efficient and high-performance models for multilingual\n667\tASR and AST,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2509.14128, 2025.\n668\t[31] Y. Bengio, J. Louradour, R. Collobert, and J. Weston, “Curriculum\n669\tlearning,” in Proc. ICML, ser. ACM International Conference Proceeding\n670\tSeries, vol. 382. ACM, 2009, pp. 41–48.\n671\t[32] A. Polok, I. Medennikov, J. Černockỳ, S. Watanabe, L. Burget,\n672\tand S. Cornell, “Mind the gap: Impact of synthetic conversational\n673\tdata on multi-talker ASR and speaker diarization,” arXiv preprint\n674\tarXiv:2605.15442, 2026.\n675\t[33] I. Loshchilov and F. Hutter, “Decoupled weight decay regularization,”\n676\tin Proc. ICLR, 2019.\n677\t\n678\t\f[34] ——, “SGDR: Stochastic gradient descent with warm restarts,” in\n679\tInternational Conference on Learning Representations, 2017. [Online].\n680\tAvailable: https://openreview.net/forum?id=Skq89Scxx\n681\t[35] J.-W. Jung, W. Zhang, S. Maiti, Y. Wu, X. Wang, J.-H. Kim, Y. Matsunaga, S. Um, J. Tian, H.-J. Shim, N. Evans, J. S. Chung, S. Takamichi,\n682\tand S. Watanabe, “The text-to-speech in the wild (TITW) database,” in\n683\tInterspeech 2025. ISCA: ISCA, Aug. 2025, pp. 4798–4802.\n684\t[36] K. Hornik, M. Stinchcombe, and H. White, “Multilayer feedforward\n685\tnetworks are universal approximators,” Neural Networks, vol. 2, no. 5,\n686\tpp. 359–366, 1989. [Online]. Available: https://www.sciencedirect.com/\n687\tscience/article/pii/0893608089900208\n688\t[37] Y. Liao, Z. Zhang, Z. Sun, Y. Sun, X. Zheng, and X. He, “Beyond\n689\twaveform robustness: Robust feature-vocoder adversarial attacks on\n690\tautomatic speech recognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.05678, 2026.\n691\t[38] W.-C. Huang and T. Toda, “Attacking UTMOS: Probing the robustness\n692\tof a speech quality assessment model,” 2026. [Online]. Available:\n693\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2606.31105\n694\t\n695\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8f71eaee-e93d-4958-8062-7f643a4adfc3", "uuid": "abcdac90-8990-4f5e-a530-9e8d7d945fc7", "timestamp": "2026-07-13T06:37:04.180Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/merl_real_tse.txt", "content": "Technical Report for MERL’s Real-TSE\nChallenge Submission\nDominik Klement∗1,2 , Yoshiki Masuyama1 , Christoph Boeddeker1 ,\nKohei Saijo3 , Julius Richter1 , Gordon Wichern1 , Jonathan Le Roux1\n1\n\narXiv:2607.09043v1 [eess.AS] 10 Jul 2026\n\n2\n\nMitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories, Cambridge, USA,\nSpeech@FIT, Brno University of Technology, Czechia, 3 Mitsubishi Electric Corporation, Kanagawa, Japan\n\nAbstract—Target speech extraction (TSE) has largely been\ndominated by neural network-based approaches trained and\nevaluated on synthetic fully overlapped data. The Real-TSE\nChallenge aims to advance performance on real-world farfield noisy and reverberant recordings. This technical report\ndescribes MERL’s submission to the Real-TSE Challenge. Rather\nthan proposing a novel model architecture, we built upon the\nbaseline model and focused primarily on data preparation and\ncleaning. Our system was trained in four stages, beginning\nwith pre-training on fully overlapped mixtures and simulated\nmulti-talker conversations with noise and reverberation applied\nto both the mixture and the enrollment utterances. We then\nadapted the model to real-world conditions using noisy farfield recordings with pseudo-targets derived from processed\nclose-talk microphone signals. Our submission achieved first\nplace in the second track, demonstrating the critical importance\nof high-quality data preparation. Furthermore, we observed\nthat DNSMOS and speaker similarity are susceptible to overoptimization, motivating an investigation of their robustness using\nadversarial attacks. The results show that both metrics can be\ndriven to extreme values without degrading the token error rate\nor the VAD-based F1 score.\nIndex Terms—Target speaker extraction, Speech Separation\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nTarget speaker extraction (TSE) aims to extract a speaker\nof interest from a speech mixture, potentially corrupted by\nnoise or reverberation. Many existing approaches are trained\nand evaluated on simulated datasets, such as Libri2Mix [1],\nwhere they achieve improvements exceeding 20 dB SI-SDRi.\nHowever, these models often fail to generalize to real-world\nrecordings, such as CHiME-6 [2] and DipCo [3], which exhibit substantially more challenging acoustic conditions. This\nperformance degradation is primarily caused by the domain\ngap between simulated training data and real-world evaluation\ndata.\nTo address this challenge, the authors of the Real-T\ndataset [4] introduced a challenging development and evaluation benchmark comprising both English and Chinese recordings. The long recordings are post-processed into conversational speech mixtures of up to one minute in duration with\nmultiple speakers.\nIn this report, we present our submission to the RealTSE\nChallenge, which builds on the baseline model architecture.\nRather than developing a more powerful model, we focus on\n∗ Work done while Dominik Klement was an intern at MERL.\n\ndata preprocessing and training with real far-field conversational mixtures. Our results demonstrate that strong performance can be achieved with a relatively simple model when\npaired with an effective data processing and training pipeline.\nII. M ODEL\nWe decided to use one of the provided baseline models\nBand-split RNN (BSRNN) with multi-level speaker conditioning [5] that utilizes per-frame and pooled speaker embeddings\nfor speaker conditioning.\nCompared to the baseline configuration, we replaced\nEcapaTDNN-512 with EcapaTDNN-1024 [6], which is a\nlarger and more powerful speaker embedding model. We also\nincreased the depth of the BSRNN model from 6 to 10\nblocks. This modification significantly improved the extraction\nperformance.\nIII. DATA P ROCESSING\nIn this section, we describe our multi-stage data processing pipeline, consisting of cleaning single-speaker data for\nsimulated pre-training and processing far-field and close-talk\nmixture pairs for real noisy data training.\nA. Pre-training Speech Data Processing\nWe combine data from multiple open datasets containing vast amounts of speakers and speaking style variability:\nLibriSpeech [7], VoxCeleb2 [8], Emilia-YODAS English and\nChinese [9], VCTK [10], and EARS [11].\nFirst, we applied ClearerVoice [12] speech enhancement\nmodels based on masking MOSSFormer [13] to preprocess\nthe noisy corpora such as VoxCeleb2 and Emilia-YODAS.\nThen, we computed speaker cosine similarity between the\noriginal and the enhanced recordings using a pre-trained\nResNet34 model from WeSpeaker [14] to further filter out\ndata with speaker similarity lower than 0.85. We observed that\nthe outliers with speaker similarity lower than 0.5 contained\nmultiple speakers or severe degradation that the enhancement\ncould not clean up. Furthermore, we applied another filtering\nto only consider audio with DNSMOS above 3.0. Even though\na high DNSMOS score does not guarantee clean speech, this\nfiltering step ensured that the enhancement likely produced\nestimates accurate enough for training.\nAfterwards, we computed word-level alignments using\nMontreal Forced Aligner (MFA) [15] to avoid sampling nonspeech segments as target speaker enrollments. Although such\n\n\fsegments could help train the model not to always expect the\ntarget speaker to be present in the mixture, they would make\nit difficult to precisely control their proportion during training.\nInstead, with a probability of 5%, we explicitly generated nontarget samples by pairing the enrollment with a speaker absent\nfrom the input mixture and trained the model to produce a zero\noutput.\nB. Noises and Room Impulse Responses\nWe applied room impulse responses (RIRs) on a clean\ninput mixture and enrollment independently with a probability\nof 0.8. The RIRs were randomly sampled from DNS4 [16]\nand from synthetic impulse responses simulated using Pyroomacoustics [17] with weights 0.8 and 0.2, respectively. We\npurposely simulated larger rooms to cover the scenarios of\nextreme echoes.\nFurthermore, to increase the robustness against multiple\nnoises, we used the following noise databases containing\nmore stationary and also impulsive noises: CHiME-3 [18],\nDEMAND [19], DNS4 [16], FMA [20], FSD50K [21], MUSAN [22], WHAM! [23], and simulated Wind noises from the\nURGENT challenge [24].\nWe used weighted sampling to increase the weight towards\nthe stationary-like noises, where we set the probability of\nsampling CHiME3, WHAM!, and Wind noises to 0.15, and\nthe probability of all the other noises to 0.11. We randomly\nsampled SNR from a [−5, 15] dB range and added the noise to\nthe input mixture and enrollment with probability 0.8. Mixture\nand enrollment noises were selected independently, covering\nall combinations of clean and noisy mixture and enrollment\npairs during training.\nC. Real Data Processing\nTo include real-world data for training, we utilized CHiME6 [2], AMI [25], AISHELL-4 [26], and AISHELL-5 [27]. As\nAISHELL-5 provides close-talk recordings that are already\nsynchronized with far-field microphones and do not contain\nsignificant cross-talk, we only perform speech enhancement\nusing ClearerVoice. For AISHELL-4, we perform GSS [28]\non multi-channel audio using ground-truth speaker diarization\nand apply speech enhancement afterwards. During training, we\nuse both AISHELL datasets for simulated far-field mixtures\nonly, as both contain a low amount of overlapped speech.\nSingle-talker Far-field Mixtures: To further adapt the model\nto real noisy data, we select single-talker segments of speech\nbased on the provided dataset annotations. Then, we cut out the\nsame segment from the speaker’s close-talk microphone and\naverage all the close-talk channels if multiple are available,\nand proceed with applying ClearerVoice speech enhancement\nto denoise and dereverberate the close talk.\nTo enable training on such mixtures, we perform max-peak\ncross-correlation synchronization with maximum lag set to\none second. Afterwards, inspired by [29], we apply a causal\nWiener filter with 10 ms window (160 taps) to project the\nclose-talk signal to the corresponding far-field. To ensure that\nsuch filter can be estimated, we shift the close-talk microphone\n\nby a quarter of the width of the Wiener filter such that the farfield recording is ahead of the corresponding close-talk.\nAfter projecting the close-talk to the corresponding far-field,\nwe observed that the projected signal contains noises, caused\nby the fact that the far-field recording contains noise. Hence,\nwe apply speech enhancement once more at the very end to\nclean up the projected close-talk.\nBefore training, we use Nvidia Parakeet-V2 [30] to filter\nout all the utterances with WER higher than 30%. We do not\nperform WER-based filtering on AISHELL datasets, as these\nare relatively simple and clean data compared to CHiME-6 or\nAMI.\nDuring mixing, to prevent potential device or channel classification, we simulate far-field mixtures on-the-fly using the\nspeakers from the same session, device, and the same channel.\nReal Far-field Mixture Training: First, we find multi-talker\nconversational segments with max duration 30 s with at least 2\nactive speakers. Then, we find an enrollment for each speaker\nthat is at least 10 seconds long, the majority of which is\nspeech. Afterwards, we use the best-performing TSE model\ntrained on far-field mixtures to reduce cross-talk on CHiME6 and AMI close-talk microphones. The Parakeet-V2 ASR is\nthen used to filter out segments with WER above 50% on\nCHiME-6 and 30% on AMI, keeping the rest of the close-talk\nfar-field pairs for training. At the end, we perform synchronization and close-to-distant projection as described above, and\napply speech enhancement to get rid of the projection noise.\nIV. T RAINING C URRICULUM\nIt has been shown in [31] that multi-stage curriculum pretraining starting from easier data and gradually progressing\ntowards more challenging data increases model performance,\ngeneralization, and convergence. Therefore, we performed\ntraining in 4-stages.\nA. Fully-overlapped Pre-training\nWe start with pre-training the TSE model from scratch\nusing fully-overlapped Libri2Mix-style data simulated on-thefly with randomly sampled enrollments.\nDuring this stage, the model should learn the mapping\nbetween the enrollment and the mixture, and extract the target\nspeaker. This training phase is performed for 200k training\nsteps.\nB. Noisy Simulated Conversations\nNext, we initialize the model from the previous stage\nand train the model using on-the-fly generated conversational\nmixtures simulated by a modified FastMSS [32] simulator.\nDuring this stage, we also introduce reverberation and noise\nto increase the model’s robustness.\nC. Far-field Mixtures\nAfter the second pre-training stage, we continue training\non on-the-fly simulated far-field mixtures generated from\nsingle-talker segments of CHiME-6, AMI, AISHELL-4, and\nAISHELL-5. Enrollment utterances are randomly sampled\n\n\ffrom the same segments. Since AMI does not contain background noise, we augment both the mixtures and the enrollment utterances with artificial noise with a probability of 0.2.\n\nTABLE I\nC OMPARISON BETWEEN THE CHALLENGE BASELINE , DIFFERENT\nTRAINING STAGES AND THE ADVERSARIAL ATTACK ON THE DEV S ET.. P\nSTANDS FOR PRECISION , R FOR RECALL , AND SPK FOR SPEAKER TO\nENROLLMENT COSINE SIMILARITY. T HE MODEL IN THE LAST ROW\n\nD. Real Far-field Mixtures\n\nMARKED WITH ⋆ WAS TRAINED ONLY USING RECONSTRUCTION LOSSES\nDURING ALL STAGES .\n\nLastly, the fourth stage contains real noisy mixture training\nagainst targets that were extracted by our previous TSE model.\nTo increase the variability during this training stage, we mix\nin 20% of synthetic data, and around 30% of far-field mixtures\nfrom the third stage of training.\n\nModel\n\nTER\n\nP\n\nR\n\nF1\n\nSPK\n\nOVRL\n\nP.808\n\n1st stage\n+ 2nd stage\n+ 3rd stage\n+ 4th stage\n\n0.53\n0.44\n0.39\n0.37\n\n0.82\n0.88\n0.91\n0.93\n\n0.93\n0.88\n0.86\n0.85\n\n0.86\n0.86\n0.88\n0.88\n\n0.48\n0.47\n0.54\n0.55\n\n2.42\n2.37\n2.81\n2.84\n\n3.21\n3.15\n3.15\n3.33\n\n4 stages, Pure\n\n0.37\n\n0.93\n\n0.84\n\n0.87\n\n0.47\n\n2.89\n\n3.32\n\nV. T RAINING S ETUP\nDuring the first two stages, we optimized the following\ntime-domain loss function:\n!\nB\n1 X\ntime\n|yi − x̂i | ,\n(1)\nL\n= log\nB i=1\nwhere x̂i is the prediction and yi is the corresponding target,\nand B is the mini-batch size. Optimizing this loss instead\nof SI-SNR or SNR prevents numerical errors for zero targets (i.e., total silence). The loss function was optimized\nusing AdamW [33] optimizer with learning rate (LR) 0.0005\nand weight decay 0.001. We used the ReduceLROnPlateau1\nlearning rate scheduler according to the validation SNR. The\ntraining recordings were randomly cropped to eight seconds\nwhile target speaker speech presence was ensured according\nto the aligned word-level timestamps.\nDuring the last two stages, we used linear LR warmup for\n2k steps with peak LR set to 1e − 4 and then applied cosine\nlearning rate scheduler [34]. Because the targets are enhanced\nprojections and not the true clean signals, the phase between\nthe far-field mixture and the projected close-talk might not be\nwell aligned. Hence, we utilize magnitude-based multi-scale\nSTFT (MS-STFT) loss during the last two training stages,\ndefined as:\nLstft =\n\nK\nB X\nX\n\n∥|S(yi , wk , hk )| − |S(x̂i , wk , hk )|∥1 ,\n\n(2)\n\ni=1 k=1\n\nwhere S(yi , wk , hk ) represents STFT computed with the window length wk and hop length hk . We selected hk = 41 wk\nsamples. We used 5 window lengths: 100, 200, 400, 800, 1600,\nwhich corresponds to 6.25 ms, 12.5 ms, 25 ms, 50 ms, 100 ms.\nAs described before, during the fourth stage, we mixed in a\nsmall portion of simulated data, so that we could utilize the\ntime-domain loss Ltime on that data.\nBesides the reconstruction losses, we also utilized metricaware losses. First, we used a torch-based implementation of\nDNSMOS that allowed us to backpropagate through it and\noptimize the following loss function:\nB\n\nLMOS =\n\n1 X\n2\n(5.0 − DNSMOSovrl (x̂i )) .\nB i=1\n\n1 PyTorch - ReduceLROnPlateau\n\n(3)\n\nDNSMOS\n\nSimilarly, to slightly push the model to better preserve the\nenrollment speaker identity, we optimized a cosine similarity\nbetween the enrollment and the output:\nB\n\nLspk =\n\n1 X\npred\n1.0 − cos(eenrl\ni , ei ) ,\nB i=1\n\n(4)\n\npred\nwhere eenrl\nrepresent the corresponding speaker embedi , ei\ndings extracted using ResNet34 from the enrollment and the\nprediction, respectively.\nThe final loss for the third and fourth stage training is a\nweighted combination of all the preceeding losses:\n\nL = 10Lstft + Ltime + 0.01LMOS + Lspk ,\n\n(5)\n\nwhere Ltime is only computed on the simulated part of the\ntraining batch.\nVI. R ESULTS\nTable I shows the progressive improvements in all of the\nmetrics. First, TER significantly improves between the first\nand the second stage, proving that conversational simulated\ndata with heavy augmentations improve the TSE performance\non challenging far-field data. Furthermore, training with 3rd\nand 4th stage shows that using real noisy and reverberated\ndata for training improves the performance even further.\nIn terms of spk-sim and DNSMOS, the main improvement\ncomes from slight metric tuning, which we used to balance out\nthese metrics with TER and F1. However, we observed that\ntraining using these metrics did not improve the perceptual\nquality when listening to the extracted audio. We even observed that over-tuning to speaker similarity causes the TSE\nmodel to output target-speaker-like artifacts in the presence of\nnoise even if no one speaks. This further proves how brittle\nthe speaker similarity models are.\nTo show the effects metric optimization had on our submission, we performed a four-stage training again without\nusing the metric-aware losses during the last two stages. In\nthis case, the model was trained using Lstft on all data and\nLtime on simulated-only data. The last row (“Pure”) in Table I\nshows that we could achieve the same TER and DNSMOS\nas with metric-aware fine-tuning. Also, F 1 score only slightly\n\n\fdecreased compared to the metric-aware training model due\nto the lower recall. This was likely caused by not optimizing\nfor spk-sim, which usually forced the model to leak more\nnoise that could potentially trigger the VAD system. The only\nmetric that got significantly decreased is speaker similarity,\nwhose value remains equal to that at the end of the second\ntraining stage. After listening to a few examples between the\nmetric-optimized and the pure model, we could not hear any\nsignificant difference in terms of extracted speaker identity,\nproving how overoptimistic the metric value can get once we\nstart optimizing it.\n\nAlgorithm 1: Metric Attack.\ndef attack(inp, enrl):\ndelta = nn.Parameter(torch.zeros_like(inp))\noptim = Adam([delta], lr=1e-3)\nfor i in range(200):\ndelta_t = tanh(delta) * 0.01\naudio_t = (inp + delta_t).clamp(-1, 1)\nloss = (stft(audio_t).abs() - stft(inp).abs())\nloss = loss.pow().mean()\nloss = loss + (5.0 - dnsmos(inp))ˆ2\nloss = loss + (1.0 - spksim(inp, enrl))\noptim.zero_grads()\nloss.backward()\noptim.step()\n\nVII. M ETRIC ATTACK\n“When a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be\na good measure.”\n— Goodhart’s law\nMany speech separation and target speech extraction systems optimize evaluation metrics either explicitly or implicitly during training, including metrics such as SI-SDR and\nPESQ. From the perspective of Goodhart’s Law, this practice\nfundamentally compromises the validity of such metrics as\nevaluation tools: once a metric becomes an optimization target,\nit ceases to function as an independent measure of system\nquality.\nThis issue is particularly evident for non-intrusive neuralnetwork-based metrics. For example, clean speech recordings\nfrom datasets such as VCTK achieve DNSMOS scores of only\naround 3.2 [35]. Therefore, observing multiple leaderboard\nsubmissions with DNSMOS scores exceeding 3.5 raised concerns about the susceptibility of model-based metrics to overoptimization.\nNeural networks are universal function approximators that\ncan approximate arbitrary functions given sufficient capacity\nand width [36]. Consequently, when a metric is directly\noptimized during training, a sufficiently expressive model\ncan effectively learn the metric itself and, in the extreme\ncase, internalize at training time an adversarial attack required\nto maximize its score. The main technical challenge to do\nso is carefully balancing the optimization process to avoid\ndegrading performance on other evaluation criteria such as\nTER and F1. Given the better-than-clean-speech DNSMOS\nscores we observed on the leaderboard, we suspect some teams\nmay have unintentionally performed such an adversarial attack.\nTo demonstrate the upper bound of metric-aware training\nand illustrate how metric optimization during training can\ninvalidate the optimized metrics as evaluation measures, we\nconducted a series of per-utterance adversarial attacks using\ndifferent metric combinations. We were surprised by how\neasily a barely perceptible perturbation could be added to the\ntarget speech extraction output waveform, yielding state-ofthe-art (but perceptually meaningless) DNSMOS and speakersimilarity scores while preserving performance on the remaining metrics, including TER and F1.\nWe based our attack algorithm on [37], which is straightforward and described in Algorithm 1. It performs 200 steps,\nin which we first calculate a small delta and add it to the\n\nreturn audio_t\n\nwaveform, then compute all the losses and sum them with\nunit weights. It is important to note that we heavily regularize\nthe adversarial noise energy and also minimize the difference\nbetween the original and modified magnitude spectrograms\nto prevent large changes. Finally, we backpropagate the loss\ngradients through the metric models and update the delta using\nthe Adam optimizer. We observed during the experiments that\nno special loss weights, learning rate, or number of steps\ntuning was required for successful convergence, proving the\nsimplicity of the attack.\nTABLE II\nC OMPARISON BETWEEN BEFORE AND AFTER METRIC ATTACK .\nAttack\n\nTER\n\nP\n\nR\n\nF1\n\nSPK\n\nNone\nDNSMOS\nSPK-SIM (EN)\n+ DNSMOS\n+ SPK-SIM (CN)\n\n0.37\n0.37\n0.37\n0.37\n0.37\n\n0.94\n0.94\n0.94\n0.94\n0.94\n\n0.85\n0.85\n0.85\n0.85\n0.85\n\n0.88\n0.88\n0.88\n0.88\n0.88\n\n0.52\n0.52\n0.82\n0.82\n0.99\n\nDNSMOS\nOVRL P808\n2.83\n4.18\n2.80\n4.11\n4.07\n\n3.33\n3.33\n3.33\n3.33\n3.33\n\nTable II shows the model results before the adversarial\nattack in the first row. It can be seen that attacking DNSMOS\nonly (2nd row) does not change the unattacked metrics. Also,\nwe can see that attacking only the English spk-sim model does\nnot achieve an overall score close to 1, as the Chinese speaker\nsimilarity stays at around 0.5 even after the attack. The last row\nshows the scenario where DNSMOS and speaker models for\nEnglish and Chinese are attacked. Once again, we can see that\nTER and F1 stayed the same, while spk-sim and DNSMOS\nare achieving their extremes. It is noteworthy to observe that\nattacking only DNSMOS achieves the best DNSMOS score\nout of all the attacks. The score decreases as we increase\nthe number of simultaneously-attacked metrics. However, the\nrelative change in DNSMOS between attacking all the metrics\nand only DNSMOS is negligible relative to its value.\nGiven the fragility of non-intrusive metrics as demonstrated\nby our attack and also shown in [37], [38], we suggest that\nthe Challenge Organizers either remove DNSMOS and spksim when calculating the official ranking or replace them\n\n\fwith alternative speech quality and speaker similarity metrics\nthat were not attacked either advertently or inadvertently by\nsubmitted systems.\nVIII. C ONCLUSION\nIn this work, we described our submission to the RealTSE\nchallenge, consisting of the baseline TSE model architecture and multi-stage data processing and training curriculum.\nOur results confirmed that each training stage improved the\nmetrics, proving that thorough data preparation with heavy\nmixture and enrollment augmentations and real noisy data\ntraining can push the performance even further. We also\nshowed that metrics such as speaker similarity or DNSMOS\nare brittle and susceptible to adversarial attacks. To push it\nto the extreme, we applied a per-waveform adversarial attack,\nwhich serves as an upperbound of what can be potentially\nachieved with training-time optimization if enough capacity\nand training balance is achieved. This raises challenges for the\norganization of future challenges in an age where generative\nmodels are thriving, and suggests the need for further metric\ndevelopment, which will be focus of our future work.\nR EFERENCES\n[1] J. Cosentino, M. Pariente, S. Cornell, A. Deleforge, and E. Vincent,\n“LibriMix: An open-source dataset for generalizable speech separation,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2005.11262, 2020.\n[2] S. Watanabe, M. Mandel, J. Barker, E. Vincent, A. Arora, X. Chang,\nS. Khudanpur, V. Manohar, D. Povey, D. Raj, D. Snyder, A. S. Subramanian, J. Trmal, B. B. Yair, C. Boeddeker, Z. Ni, Y. Fujita, S. Horiguchi,\nN. Kanda, T. Yoshioka, and N. Ryant, “CHiME-6 challenge: Tackling\nmultispeaker speech recognition for unsegmented recordings,” in Proc.\n6th International Workshop on Speech Processing in Everyday Environments (CHiME 2020), 2020, pp. 1–7.\n[3] M. Van Segbroeck, A. Zaid, K. Kutsenko, C. Huerta, T. Nguyen, X. Luo,\nB. Hoffmeister, J. Trmal, M. Omologo, and R. Maas, “DiPCo – dinner\nparty corpus,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2020, pp. 434–436.\n[4] S. Li, S. Wang, J. Han, K. Zhang, W. Wang, and H. Li, “REAL-T:\nReal conversational mixtures for target speaker extraction,” in Proc.\nInterspeech, 2025, pp. 1923–1927.\n[5] K. Zhang, J. Li, S. Wang, Y. Wei, Y. Wang, Y. Wang, and H. Li,\n“Multi-level speaker representation for target speaker extraction,” in\nProc. ICASSP, 2025.\n[6] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck, “ECAPA-TDNN:\nEmphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in TDNN\nbased speaker verification,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2020, pp. 3830–3834.\n[7] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “LibriSpeech: An\nASR corpus based on public domain audio books,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n[8] J. S. Chung, A. Nagrani, and A. Zisserman, “VoxCeleb2: Deep speaker\nrecognition,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2018, pp. 1086–1090.\n[9] H. He, Z. Shang, C. Wang, X. Li, Y. Gu, H. Hua, L. Liu, C. Yang,\nJ. Li, P. Shi, Y. Wang, K. Chen, P. Zhang, and Z. Wu, “Emilia: A largescale, extensive, multilingual, and diverse dataset for speech generation,”\nIEEE/ACM Trans. Audio, Speech, Lang. Process., vol. 33, pp. 4044–\n4054, 2025.\n[10] J. Yamagishi, C. Veaux, and K. MacDonald, “CSTR VCTK Corpus:\nEnglish multi-speaker corpus for CSTR voice cloning toolkit (version\n0.92),” 2019.\n[11] J. Richter, Y.-C. Wu, S. Krenn, S. Welker, B. Lay, S. Watanabe,\nA. Richard, and T. Gerkmann, “EARS: An anechoic fullband speech\ndataset benchmarked for speech enhancement and dereverberation,” in\nProc. Interspeech, 2024, pp. 4873–4877.\n[12] S. Zhao, Z. Pan, and B. Ma, “ClearerVoice-Studio: Bridging advanced\nspeech processing research and practical deployment,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2025, pp. 2980–2984.\n\n[13] S. Zhao and B. Ma, “MossFormer: Pushing the performance limit of\nmonaural speech separation using gated single-head transformer with\nconvolution-augmented joint self-attentions,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2023.\n[14] H. Wang, C. Liang, S. Wang, Z. Chen, B. Zhang, X. Xiang, Y. Deng,\nand Y. Qian, “WeSpeaker: A research and production oriented speaker\nembedding learning toolkit,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2023.\n[15] M. McAuliffe, M. Socolof, S. Mihuc, M. Wagner, and M. Sonderegger,\n“Montreal forced aligner: Trainable text-speech alignment using Kaldi,”\nin Proc. Interspeech, 2017, pp. 498–502.\n[16] H. Dubey, V. Gopal, R. Cutler, A. Aazami, S. Matusevych, S. Braun,\nS. E. Eskimez, M. Thakker, T. Yoshioka, H. Gamper, and R. Aichner,\n“ICASSP 2022 deep noise suppression challenge,” in Proc. ICASSP,\n2022, pp. 9271–9275.\n[17] R. Scheibler, E. Bezzam, and I. Dokmanić, “Pyroomacoustics: A python\npackage for audio room simulation and array processing algorithms,” in\nProc. ICASSP, 2018, pp. 351–355.\n[18] J. Barker, R. Marxer, E. Vincent, and S. Watanabe, “The third CHiME\nspeech separation and recognition challenge: Dataset, task and baselines,” in Proc. ASRU, Dec. 2015, pp. 504–511.\n[19] J. Thiemann, N. Ito, and E. Vincent, “The diverse environments multichannel acoustic noise database (DEMAND): A database of multichannel environmental noise recordings,” in Proceedings of Meetings on\nAcoustics, vol. 19, no. 1. Acoustical Society of America, 2013, p.\n035081.\n[20] M. Defferrard, K. Benzi, P. Vandergheynst, and X. Bresson, “FMA: A\ndataset for music analysis,” in Proc. ISMIR, 2017, pp. 316–323.\n[21] E. Fonseca, X. Favory, J. Pons, F. Font, and X. Serra, “FSD50K: An\nopen dataset of human-labeled sound events,” IEEE/ACM Trans. Audio,\nSpeech, Lang. Process., vol. 30, pp. 829–852, 2022.\n[22] D. Snyder, G. Chen, and D. Povey, “MUSAN: A music, speech, and\nnoise corpus,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1510.08484, 2015.\n[23] G. Wichern, J. Antognini, M. Flynn, L. R. Zhu, E. McQuinn, D. Crow,\nE. Manilow, and J. Le Roux, “WHAM!: Extending speech separation to\nnoisy environments,” in Interspeech 2019, 2019.\n[24] W. Zhang, R. Scheibler, K. Saijo, S. Cornell, C. Li, Z. Ni, J. Pirklbauer, M. Sach, S. Watanabe, T. Fingscheidt, and Y. Qian, “URGENT\nchallenge: Universality, robustness, and generalizability for speech enhancement,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2024, pp. 4868–4872.\n[25] J. Carletta, S. Ashby, S. Bourban, M. Flynn, M. Guillemot, T. Hain,\nJ. Kadlec, V. Karaiskos, W. Kraaij, M. Kronenthal et al., “The AMI\nmeeting corpus: A pre-announcement,” in International workshop on\nmachine learning for multimodal interaction. Springer, 2005, pp. 28–\n39.\n[26] Y. Fu, L. Cheng, S. Lv, Y. Jv, Y. Kong, Z. Chen, Y. Hu, L. Xie, J. Wu,\nH. Bu, X. Xu, J. Du, and J. Chen, “AISHELL-4: An open source dataset\nfor speech enhancement, separation, recognition and speaker diarization\nin conference scenario,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2021, pp. 3665–3669.\n[27] Y. Dai, H. Wang, X. Li, Z. Zhang, S. Wang, L. Xie, X. Xu, H. Guo,\nS. Zhang, H. Bu, and W. Chen, “AISHELL-5: The first open-source\nin-car multi-channel multi-speaker speech dataset for automatic speech\ndiarization and recognition,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2025, pp. 5493–5497.\n[28] C. Boeddecker, J. Heitkaemper, J. Schmalenstroeer, L. Drude, J. Heymann, and R. Haeb-Umbach, “Front-end processing for the CHiME-5\ndinner party scenario,” in Proc. 5th International Workshop on Speech\nProcessing in Everyday Environments (CHiME 2018), 2018, pp. 35–40.\n[29] T. Nakatani, R. Ikeshita, N. Kamo, M. Delcroix, and S. Araki, “Generating training targets for real-world speech enhancement via closeto-distant microphone projection,” in Proc. ICASSP, 2026, pp. 18 912–\n18 916.\n[30] M. Sekoyan, N. R. Koluguri, N. Tadevosyan, P. Zelasko, T. Bartley,\nN. Karpov, J. Balam, and B. Ginsburg, “Canary-1B-V2 & ParakeetTDT-0.6B-V3: Efficient and high-performance models for multilingual\nASR and AST,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2509.14128, 2025.\n[31] Y. Bengio, J. Louradour, R. Collobert, and J. Weston, “Curriculum\nlearning,” in Proc. ICML, ser. ACM International Conference Proceeding\nSeries, vol. 382. ACM, 2009, pp. 41–48.\n[32] A. Polok, I. Medennikov, J. Černockỳ, S. Watanabe, L. Burget,\nand S. Cornell, “Mind the gap: Impact of synthetic conversational\ndata on multi-talker ASR and speaker diarization,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2605.15442, 2026.\n[33] I. Loshchilov and F. Hutter, “Decoupled weight decay regularization,”\nin Proc. ICLR, 2019.\n\n\f[34] ——, “SGDR: Stochastic gradient descent with warm restarts,” in\nInternational Conference on Learning Representations, 2017. [Online].\nAvailable: https://openreview.net/forum?id=Skq89Scxx\n[35] J.-W. Jung, W. Zhang, S. Maiti, Y. Wu, X. Wang, J.-H. Kim, Y. Matsunaga, S. Um, J. Tian, H.-J. Shim, N. Evans, J. S. Chung, S. Takamichi,\nand S. Watanabe, “The text-to-speech in the wild (TITW) database,” in\nInterspeech 2025. ISCA: ISCA, Aug. 2025, pp. 4798–4802.\n[36] K. Hornik, M. Stinchcombe, and H. White, “Multilayer feedforward\nnetworks are universal approximators,” Neural Networks, vol. 2, no. 5,\npp. 359–366, 1989. [Online]. Available: https://www.sciencedirect.com/\nscience/article/pii/0893608089900208\n[37] Y. Liao, Z. Zhang, Z. Sun, Y. Sun, X. Zheng, and X. He, “Beyond\nwaveform robustness: Robust feature-vocoder adversarial attacks on\nautomatic speech recognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.05678, 2026.\n[38] W.-C. Huang and T. Toda, “Attacking UTMOS: Probing the robustness\nof a speech quality assessment model,” 2026. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2606.31105\n\n\f", "numLines": 695, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 695}}}
